Using the attached GlassDoor review data, perform sentiment analyses and topic models for the reviews.

The reviews are broken into 3 separate parts: pros, cons, and advice. You can choose to perform your analyses on any of these pieces (or combine them in any way you wish). After analyzing the text, determine if there are any text features that can be used to predict any of the ratings (e.g., rating, workLifeRating, management).

While the text is generally clean, you will find where some words have ran together – we have seen the fix for this before. You might even encounter non-English texts.


load("glassDoor.RData")

Data Cleaning

Sentiment Analysis

Get positive comments together within each rating levels.


clean_glassDoor1 <- clean_glassDoor%>%
  group_by(rating)%>%
  summarise(pros = paste0(pros,collapse = " "),
         pros = str_squish(pros))

By looking into the average sentiment scores under each rating levels, we could find that if we assign a sentiment score for each levels, rating is increased as sentiment score increase.


library(sentimentr)
rawsentiment <-sentiment(clean_glassDoor1$pros, polarity_dt = lexicon::hash_sentiment_nrc)

#Adding rating column to rawsentiment dataframe for inner join
AvgSentiment <- rawsentiment%>%
  mutate(rating = c(4,3,5,2,1))%>%
  select(word_count,sentiment,rating)%>%
  arrange(desc(rating))

dtm1 <- TermDocumentMatrix(rating1)

But as there are many overlap between the frenquent terms under each rating level, it requires more manual lookup comparing with topic model in finding the relationship between specific words and rating. One of the reasons that lead to this problem might be using only pros text in the sentiment analysis.

Topic Model

Since topic models are great for predicting topic probabilities for unseen document, we could use it in predicting rating using the text we have.


set.seed(1001)

# partition of Data
holdoutRows = sample(1:nrow(clean_glassDoor), 100, replace = FALSE)

clean_glassDoor$rating = as.numeric(clean_glassDoor$rating)
prosText = textProcessor(documents = clean_glassDoor$pros[-c(holdoutRows)], 
                          metadata = clean_glassDoor[-c(holdoutRows), ], 
                          stem = FALSE)

Building corpus... 
Converting to Lower Case... 
Removing punctuation... 
Removing stopwords... 
Removing numbers... 
Creating Output... 

textPrep = prepDocuments(documents = prosText$documents, 
                               vocab = prosText$vocab,
                               meta = prosText$meta)

Removing 2081 of 3821 terms (2081 of 23591 tokens) due to frequency 
Removing 1 Documents with No Words 
Your corpus now has 1730 documents, 1740 terms and 21510 tokens.

The 4 plots below help us find the optimal number of topics to take, and we should select the number of topics with relatively high semantic coherence and low residual. Therefore, the model with 4 topics is picked here. It has a reasonable trade-off between high sematic coherence and residual, also it has low held-out-likelyhood, which means it’s less likely to generate a suprising result with new words.


kTest = searchK(documents = textPrep$documents,  vocab = textPrep$vocab, 
                    K=c(3, 4, 5, 10, 20), verbose=FALSE)

plot(kTest)

Start our model with 4 topics and generate the top topics proportion plot.

The top topics plot below illustrates that topic 3 with good, people and managmenet as the most frequet words counts almost 30% of all topics words. Topic 1, 2,and 3 are close to each other in proportion which is around 23%.


topics4 = stm(documents = textPrep$documents, 
             vocab = textPrep$vocab, seed = 1001,
             K = 4, verbose = FALSE)

plot(topics4)

Label topics function will gives us a summary of highest, frex, lift and score. For example, frex of topic 1 tells us that words such as company, project, and staff are the most frequent terms in topic 1 but they are exclusive to other topics. This provides more insights than sentiment analysis in finding the relationship between rating and words. Score gives us an idea about how common the words are in comparison to how common they are in other topics.


labelTopics(topics4)

topicPredictor = stm(documents = textPrep$documents,
             vocab = textPrep$vocab, prevalence = ~ rating,
             data = textPrep$meta, K = 4, verbose = FALSE)


ratingEffect = estimateEffect(1:4 ~ rating, stmobj = topicPredictor,
               metadata = textPrep$meta)
ratingEffect$rating <- as.numeric(ratingEffect$rating)
summary(ratingEffect, topics = c(1:4))

These plots are more straight forward in explaining the relationship between rating and the words in pros. From the topic 1 plot, we can tell that as the proportion of topic 1 words increased, rating is also increased. Topic 2 plot does not illustrate a clear relationship between rating and the topic 2 words. Words under topic 3 demonstrate a negtive relationship with rating. For the last plot, as the proportion of topic 4 words increase, rating will also increase. A more complete picture requires more advices feed into the model.


plot.estimateEffect(ratingEffect, "rating", method = "continuous",
                    model = topicPredictor, topics = 1, labeltype = "frex")


plot.estimateEffect(ratingEffect, "rating", method = "continuous",
                    model = topicPredictor, topics = 2, labeltype = "frex")
